<!-- AUTHOR NOTE -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="section-number">Author's Note</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">A Note on <span>Contrarian Thinking</span></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">This thesis is a deliberate exercise in second-order thinking — examining what most market participants overlook by stopping at the first-order conclusion.</p>
  <p class="body-text">The dominant market narrative frames AI leadership as a zero-sum race. Under this framework, the United States wins, China challenges, and India falls behind. The investment implication appears obvious: overweight AI leaders, underweight laggards.</p>
  <p class="body-text">This thesis challenges that framing — not by dismissing AI's transformative potential, but by questioning whether the current phase of the AI investment cycle necessarily creates the best economic outcomes for early participants.</p>
  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>Is India missing the AI revolution? Or is India avoiding the most expensive phase of it?</p>
    <cite>— Core Question · Sahu Capital</cite>
  </div>
  <p class="body-text">History provides a surprisingly consistent answer. In several previous technology cycles — railways, radio, internet infrastructure, telecom networks, renewable energy — the greatest economic beneficiaries were not always the earliest investors. They were often the economies and enterprises that adopted proven technologies <strong>after infrastructure costs collapsed, business models matured, and speculative capital was removed from the system.</strong></p>
</div>

<!-- SECTION 1 — THE AI INVESTMENT CONTEXT -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="section-number">Section 01</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">The <span>AI Investment</span> Context</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Understanding the scale of the current AI capital expenditure cycle — and why history suggests caution alongside enthusiasm.</p>
  <p class="body-text">Global AI enthusiasm has produced one of the largest coordinated capital allocation waves in modern financial history. Billions of dollars are being committed toward semiconductor fabrication, data centers, AI infrastructure, foundation models, and compute networks simultaneously.</p>

  <!-- LIVE DATA STRIP -->
  <div class="data-strip">
    <div class="data-item">
      <div class="data-label">GPT-3 Training Cost (2020)</div>
      <div class="data-value">$4.6M</div>
      <div class="data-note">Original estimate · OpenAI</div>
    </div>
    <div class="data-item">
      <div class="data-label">GPT-4 Training Cost (2023)</div>
      <div class="data-value">$100M+</div>
      <div class="data-note">Estimated compute cost</div>
    </div>
    <div class="data-item">
      <div class="data-label">GPT-5 Training Cost (2025)</div>
      <div class="data-value">$1.25B+</div>
      <div class="data-note">Total estimated training</div>
    </div>
    <div class="data-item">
      <div class="data-label">Inference Cost Reduction</div>
      <div class="data-value">280x</div>
      <div class="data-note">In 18 months · Stanford AI Index</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The data reveals a striking asymmetry. <strong>Training costs at the frontier are escalating exponentially</strong> — GPT-5 cost over 270 times more to train than GPT-3. Yet simultaneously, <strong>inference costs — the cost of actually using AI — have collapsed 280-fold in 18 months.</strong></p>
  <p class="body-text">This divergence is critical to the late-mover thesis. The entities bearing the enormous costs of frontier AI development are largely concentrated in a handful of US and Chinese technology giants. The entities that will eventually consume the outputs — at drastically reduced costs — could be distributed globally, including India.</p>

  <!-- CHART 1 — AI TRAINING COST ESCALATION -->
  <div class="chart-wrap">
    <div class="chart-title">Chart 01 — Frontier AI Training Cost Escalation vs Inference Cost Collapse</div>
    <div class="chart-subtitle">Training costs at the frontier grow exponentially while inference costs collapse — creating a future window for low-cost AI adoption.</div>
    <div class="chart-canvas-wrap"><canvas id="chart1"></canvas></div>
    <div class="chart-source">Source: Stanford AI Index 2025, Epoch AI, OpenAI estimates · Compiled by Sahu Capital</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The investment implication is profound. Countries and companies bearing the pioneer cost of AI today are funding the infrastructure that late movers will eventually access at a fraction of the original price. <strong>This has happened in every major technology cycle in modern history.</strong></p>
</div>

