<!-- SECTION 3 — INDIA'S FOUR STRUCTURAL ADVANTAGES -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="section-number">Section 03</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">India's Four <span>Structural Advantages</span></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Why India's position in the AI cycle may be structurally superior to what the conventional narrative suggests.</p>

  <div class="advantage-grid">
    <div class="advantage-card">
      <div class="adv-number">01</div>
      <div class="adv-title">Lower Labour Cost Reduces Automation Urgency</div>
      <div class="adv-text">Unlike developed economies facing acute labour shortages and rising wage inflation, India does not face the same economic pressure to replace workers with AI. The cost-benefit calculus for large-scale AI deployment remains less compelling than in Western markets — allowing India to delay expensive AI infrastructure investments until technology becomes cheaper and commercially proven.</div>
      <div class="adv-data">India avg. monthly wage ~₹25,000 vs US ~$5,800 · Labour arbitrage remains substantial</div>
    </div>
    <div class="advantage-card">
      <div class="adv-number">02</div>
      <div class="adv-title">Avoiding Early-Adopter Capital Destruction</div>
      <div class="adv-text">The first phase of every technological revolution attracts excessive capital. Many projects fail. Many business models disappear. Many valuations collapse. India may avoid this phase entirely — acquiring mature AI capabilities at substantially lower costs rather than financing the expensive and uncertain experimentation phase currently underway in the US and China.</div>
      <div class="adv-data">Inference costs already fell 280x in 18 months · Cost curve collapse ongoing</div>
    </div>
    <div class="advantage-card">
      <div class="adv-number">03</div>
      <div class="adv-title">Employment Preservation During Demographic Expansion</div>
      <div class="adv-text">India remains one of the few major economies with a genuinely growing workforce. Rapid, premature automation may create significant social and economic challenges if implemented before sufficient alternative employment opportunities exist. A measured adoption path may allow productivity gains to materialize without large-scale labour displacement — preserving social stability during a critical growth phase.</div>
      <div class="adv-data">India adds ~12 million new workers annually · World's largest youth population</div>
    </div>
    <div class="advantage-card">
      <div class="adv-number">04</div>
      <div class="adv-title">The Leapfrogging Capability</div>
      <div class="adv-text">India has demonstrated a remarkable and repeated ability to bypass legacy technology generations entirely — adopting mature, cost-optimized solutions that skip the expensive intermediate stages. This structural capability may allow India to adopt mature AI architectures after costs decline significantly, skipping early-generation systems entirely — just as it did with payments, telecoms, and mobile banking.</div>
      <div class="adv-data">UPI now processes 49% of global real-time payments · Built in under 10 years</div>
    </div>
