<!-- SECTION 5 — CONCENTRATION RISK -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="section-number">Section 05</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">The <span>Concentration Risk</span> Nobody Is Discussing</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">When national economic fortunes become tied to single technology companies — and what history says about what comes next.</p>
  <p class="body-text">The current AI boom has created extraordinary market concentration. Taiwan's equity market has become increasingly dependent on TSMC. South Korea's market performance is heavily influenced by Samsung Electronics and SK Hynix. The United States market is increasingly driven by a narrow group of AI infrastructure beneficiaries.</p>
  <p class="body-text">This concentration is not unprecedented. History provides two instructive precedents where similar concentration dynamics ultimately created significant systemic risk — regardless of the underlying quality of the businesses involved.</p>

  <div class="concentration-grid">
    <div class="conc-card">
      <div class="conc-country">Finland</div>
      <div class="conc-company">Nokia</div>
      <div class="conc-peak">~70%</div>
      <div class="conc-desc">At its dotcom peak in 2000, Nokia represented approximately 70% of Finland's equity market capitalisation and 30% of the country's entire GDP — paying almost a quarter of all Finnish corporate taxes. The company appeared structurally unassailable as the world's dominant mobile phone manufacturer. Technological disruption by Apple's iPhone and Android proved otherwise. Finland's extreme market concentration amplified the economic damage of a single company's decline dramatically.</div>
      <div class="conc-warning">Outcome: 90%+ value destruction · 30% of Finnish GDP at peak</div>
    </div>
    <div class="conc-card">
      <div class="conc-country">Denmark</div>
      <div class="conc-company">Novo Nordisk</div>
      <div class="conc-peak">~57%</div>
      <div class="conc-desc">Novo Nordisk's success with GLP-1 weight loss drugs elevated Denmark's market capitalization to levels exceeding the country's GDP. The company became the most valuable in Europe. While Novo Nordisk remains an exceptional business, concentration risk at this scale introduces a different form of vulnerability — particularly if competitive dynamics shift.</div>
      <div class="conc-warning">Still unresolved — concentration risk remains elevated</div>
    </div>
    <div class="conc-card">
      <div class="conc-country">Taiwan</div>
      <div class="conc-company">TSMC</div>
      <div class="conc-peak">42%+</div>
      <div class="conc-desc">TSMC now accounts for over 42% of Taiwan's benchmark TAIEX index — and over 50% of the MSCI Taiwan Index. The company's market cap of ~$2.26 trillion as of June 2026 is equivalent to approximately 150% of Taiwan's entire GDP. Taiwan's financial regulator changed fund rules specifically to allow more TSMC investment — underscoring how deeply the market has become dependent on a single name.</div>
      <div class="conc-warning">TSMC ~150% of Taiwan GDP · 42%+ of TAIEX · 50%+ of MSCI Taiwan</div>
    </div>
    <div class="conc-card">
      <div class="conc-country">South Korea</div>
      <div class="conc-company">Samsung + SK Hynix</div>
      <div class="conc-peak">~47–50%</div>
      <div class="conc-desc">Samsung Electronics and SK Hynix combined now account for approximately 47–50% of the KOSPI index — the highest concentration level in over a year, approaching half the entire South Korean market. Samsung accounts for ~26% and SK Hynix ~21% individually. Korea has become the only country outside the US with two companies simultaneously valued above $1 trillion. SK Hynix surged 274% in 2025 and 188% in 2026.</div>
      <div class="conc-warning">~47–50% of KOSPI · Two $1T+ companies · Highest concentration in 16 months</div>
    </div>
  </div>

